[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/particle-filter-p02] The term "Sampling Importance Resampling" is also sometimes used when referring to SIR filters, but the term *Importance Resampling* is more accurate because the word "resampling" implies that the initial sampling has already been done.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/particle-filter-p02] Sequential importance sampling (SIS) is the same as the SIR algorithm but without the resampling stage.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/particle-filter-p02] This version often exhibits particle weight collapse, where all the probability gets concentrated on one or two particles, and the rest of the particle weights correspond to very small probability.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/particle-filter-p02] The introduction of resampling alleviates this problem.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/particle-filter-p02] The "direct version" algorithm is rather simple (compared to other particle filtering algorithms) and it uses composition and rejection.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/particle-filter-p02] The goal is to generate P "particles" at *k* using only the particles from $k-1$ .
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/particle-filter-p02] This requires that a Markov equation can be written (and computed) to generate a $x_{k}$ based only upon $x_{k-1}$ .
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/particle-filter-p02] This algorithm uses the composition of the P particles from $k-1$ to generate a particle at *k* and repeats (steps 2–6) until P particles are generated at *k*.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/particle-filter-p02] This can be more easily visualized if *x* is viewed as a two-dimensional array.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/particle-filter-p02] One dimension is *k* and the other dimension is the particle number.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/particle-filter-p02] For example, $x(k,i)$ would be the ith particle at k and can also be written $x_{k}^{(i)}$ (as done above in the algorithm).
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/particle-filter-p02] Step 3 generates a *potential* $x_{k}$ based on a randomly chosen particle ( $x_{k-1}^{(i)}$ ) at time $k-1$ and rejects or accepts it in step 6.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/particle-filter-p02] In other words, the $x_{k}$ values are generated using the previously generated $x_{k-1}$ .
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] The data sources for a fusion process are not specified to originate from identical sensors.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] One can distinguish *direct fusion*, *indirect fusion* and fusion of the outputs of the former two.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] Direct fusion is the fusion of sensor data from a set of heterogeneous or homogeneous sensors, soft sensors, and history values of sensor data, while indirect fusion uses information sources like *a priori* knowledge about the environment and human input.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] Sensor fusion is also known as *(multi-sensor) data fusion* and is a subset of *information fusion*.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] Two example sensor fusion calculations are illustrated below.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] Let ${x}_{1}$ and ${x}_{2}$ denote two estimates from two independent sensor measurements, with noise variances $\scriptstyle \sigma _{1}^{2}$ and $\scriptstyle \sigma _{2}^{2}$ , respectively.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] It can be seen that the fused result is simply a linear combination of the two measurements weighted by their respective information.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] It is worth noting that if ${x}$ is a random variable.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] The estimates ${x}_{1}$ and ${x}_{2}$ will be correlated through common process noise, which will cause the estimate ${x}_{3}$ to lose conservativeness.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] Another (equivalent) method to fuse two measurements is to use the optimal Kalman filter.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] Suppose that the data is generated by a first-order system and let ${\textbf {P}}_{k}$ denote the solution of the filter's Riccati equation.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] By inspection, when the first measurement is noise free, the filter ignores the second measurement and vice versa.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] That is, the combined estimate is weighted by the quality of the measurements.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] In sensor fusion, centralized versus decentralized refers to where the fusion of the data occurs.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] In centralized fusion, the clients simply forward all of the data to a central location, and some entity at the central location is responsible for correlating and fusing the data.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] In decentralized, the clients take full responsibility for fusing the data.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] Multiple combinations of centralized and decentralized systems exist.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] Another classification of sensor configuration refers to the coordination of information flow between sensors.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] These mechanisms provide a way to resolve conflicts or disagreements and to allow the development of dynamic sensing strategies.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] Sensors are in redundant (or competitive) configuration if each node delivers independent measures of the same properties.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] This configuration can be used in error correction when comparing information from multiple nodes.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] Redundant strategies are often used with high level fusions in voting procedures.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] Complementary configuration occurs when multiple information sources supply different information about the same features.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] This strategy is used for fusing information at raw data level within decision-making algorithms.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] Complementary features are typically applied in motion recognition tasks with neural network, hidden Markov model, support vector machine, clustering methods and other techniques.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] Cooperative sensor fusion uses the information extracted by multiple independent sensors to provide information that would not be available from single sensors.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] For example, sensors connected to body segments are used for the detection of the angle between them.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] Cooperative sensor strategy gives information impossible to obtain from single nodes.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] Cooperative information fusion can be used in motion recognition, gait analysis, motion analysis,,.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] There are several categories or levels of sensor fusion that are commonly used.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] Sensor fusion level can also be defined basing on the kind of information used to feed the fusion algorithm.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] More precisely, sensor fusion can be performed fusing raw data coming from different sources, extrapolated features or even decision made by single nodes.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] One application of sensor fusion is GPS/INS, where Global Positioning System and inertial navigation system data is fused using various different methods, e.g. the extended Kalman filter.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] This is useful, for example, in determining the attitude of an aircraft using low-cost sensors.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] Another example is using the data fusion approach to determine the traffic state (low traffic, traffic jam, medium flow) using road side collected acoustic, image and sensor data.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] In the field of autonomous driving, sensor fusion is used to combine the redundant information from complementary sensors in order to obtain a more accurate and reliable representation of the environment.
[src:sensor-fusion-autonomous/sensor-fusion] Although technically not a dedicated sensor fusion method, modern convolutional neural network based methods can simultaneously process many channels of sensor data (such as hyperspectral imaging with hundreds of bands ) and fuse relevant information to produce classification results.
